(137, 5, 16, 51, 'April', 'June', 'MS-V3I2P103', 'https://doi.org/10.59232/MS-V3I2P103', 'Using the Computer Model of a Single-Phase Transformer with a Middle-Point Tap in the Secondary Winding to Study the Current Stabilization System for Excitation Winding of a Commutator Traction Motor ', 22, 29, '[\"Mikhail Pustovetov\"]', 'A single-phase transformer with a tap at the middle of the secondary winding is a common element in various electrical circuits, including those onboard electric rolling stock. A typical case is the power supply from such a transformer of a single-phase full-wave mid-point thyristor converter with a freewheeling diode. The article provides a detailed description of the computer model of the said transformer developed by the author, built on the basis of a combination of circuit and operational principles of compilation. The proposed model can also be used to describe processes in a single-phase two-winding transformer without a tap, taking into account possible connection groups I/I-6 or I/I-0. An example of embedding the transformer model in a more complex computer model of the excitation current stabilization system (PI controller of current based) of traction electric motors of a DC electric locomotive is shown.', '[\"Mainline DC electric locomotive, Commutator traction motor, Mid-point thyristor converter with freewheeling diode, Excitation winding, single-phase transformer, Computer model, Current stabilization.\"]', '<p>[1] Mikhail Pustovetov, “Loaded by RL-Branch EMC Filter on the Output of the Inverter Transfer Function Taking into Account Resistances and Electric Transformer’s Transfer Function Derivation,” <em>Journal of Engineering Research and Sciences</em>, vol. 1, no. 5, pp. 102–108, 2022. </p><p>[<a href=\"https://dx.doi.org/10.55708/js0105011\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">CrossRef</a>] [<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Loaded+by+RL-Branch+EMC+Filter+on+the+Output+of+the+Inverter+Transfer+Function+Taking+into+Account+Resistances+and+Electric+Transformer%E2%80%99s+Transfer+Function+Derivation&amp;btnG=\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a href=\"https://www.jenrs.com/v01/i05/p011/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[2] Phase-Controlled Converters. [Online] Available: https://www.stannescet.ac.in/cms/staff/qbank/EEE/Notes/300691213.POWER%20ELECTRONICS%20UNIT%20II.pdf </p><p>[3] Single phase fully wave controlled full wave Rectifiers. [Online]. Available: https://drive.uqu.edu.sa/_/gmsowilam/files/Industrial%20electronics/Single%20Phase%20Fully%20Controlled%20Rectifier2009-2.pdf</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[4] Mohammed Saleem, Phase Controlled Converter, Power Electronics and Instrumentation, pp. 1-26. [Online]. Available: https://pace.edu.in/img/course/pe&amp;i_module2.pdf&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>[5] M. D. Singh, K. B.&nbsp;Khanchandani, <em>Power Electronics</em>,<em> </em>2<sup>nd</sup> ed., Tata McGraw-Hill Publishing Company Limited, New Delhi, India, 2007. </p><p>[<a href=\"https://highered.mheducation.com/sites/0070612218/information_center_view0/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[6] V.V. Litovchenko, D.V. Nazarov, and V.A. Sharov, “Simulation Model of a Direct-Current Electric Locomotive with Commutator Traction Motors,” <em>Russian Electrical Engineering</em>, vol. 91, no. 1, pp. 69-76, 2020. </p><p>[<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.3103/S1068371220010071\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">CrossRef</a>] [<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=%E2%80%9CSimulation+Model+of+a+Direct-Current+Electric+Locomotive+with+Commutator+Traction+Motors%2C&amp;btnG=\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" targ